\fs19\fsmilli9882 \cf2 \cb3 Live Activity\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa340\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Update passes as needed.
\f1\b0 \'a0Physical passes don\'92t typically change, but a digital pass can reflect updates to events. An airline boarding pass, for example, can automatically update to display flight delays and gate changes.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Use change messages only for updates to time-critical information.
\f1\b0 \'a0A change message interrupts people\'92s current workflow, so it\'92s essential to send one only when you make an update they need to know about. For example, people need to know when there\'92s a gate change in a boarding pass, but they don\'92t need to know when a customer service phone number changes. Never use a change message for marketing or other noncritical communication. Change messages are available on a per-field basis; for developer guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/WalletPasses/adding-a-web-service-to-update-passes"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Adding a Web Service to Update Passes}}.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/wallet#Designing-passes"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Designing passes}}
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Wallet uses a consistent design aesthetic to strengthen familiarity and build trust. Instead of merely replicating the appearance of a physical item, design a clean, simple pass that looks at home in Wallet.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 {{\NeXTGraphic Attachment.png \width320 \height320 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Design a pass that looks great and works well on all devices.
\f1\b0 \'a0Passes can look different on different devices. For example, when a pass appears on Apple Watch, it doesn\'92t display all the images it displays when it appears on iPhone (for guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/wallet#Passes-for-Apple-Watch"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Passes for Apple Watch}}). Don\'92t put essential information in elements that might be unavailable on certain devices. Also, don\'92t add padding to images; for example, watchOS crops white space from some images.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Avoid using device-specific language.
\f1\b0 \'a0You can\'92t predict the device people will use to view your pass, so don\'92t write text that might not make sense on a particular device. For example, text that tells people to \'93slide to view\'94 content doesn\'92t make sense when it appears on Apple Watch.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Make your pass instantly identifiable.
\f1\b0 \'a0Using color \'97 especially a color that\'92s linked to your brand \'97 can help people recognize your pass as soon as they see it. Make sure that pass content remains comfortably readable against the background you choose.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Keep the front of a pass uncluttered so people can get important information at a glance.
\f1\b0 \'a0Show essential information \'97 like an event date or account balance \'97 in the top-right area of the pass so people can still see it when the pass is collapsed in Wallet. Use the rest of the pass front to provide important information; consider putting extra information on the back of a pass (iOS) or in a details screen (watchOS).\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Prefer an NFC-compatible pass.
\f1\b0 \'a0People appreciate having a contactless pass, because it means that they can just hold their device near a reader. If you support both NFC and a barcode or QR code, the code appears on the back of the pass (in iOS) or in the details screen (in watchOS). In iOS, you can display a QR code or barcode on the front of your pass if necessary for your design.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Reduce image sizes for optimal performance.
\f1\b0 \'a0People can receive passes via email or a webpage. To make downloads as fast as possible, use the smallest image files that still look great.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Provide an icon that represents your company or brand.
\f1\b0 \'a0The system includes your icon when displaying information about a relevant pass on the Lock Screen. Mail also uses the icon to represent your pass in an email message. You can use your app icon or design an icon for this purpose.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/wallet#Pass-styles"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs39\fsmilli19765 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Pass styles}}
\fs39\fsmilli19765 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 The system defines several pass\'a0
\f4\i styles
\f1\i0 \'a0for categories like boarding pass, coupon, store card, and event ticket. Pass styles specify the appearance and layout of content in your pass, and the information that the system needs to suggest your pass when it\'92s relevant (for guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/wallet#Passes"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Passes}}).\cb1 \
\cb3 Although each pass style is different, all styles display information using the basic layout areas shown below:\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 {{\NeXTGraphic Attachment.png \width320 \height320 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cb3 All passes display a logo image, and some can display additional images in other areas depending on the pass style. To display information in the layout areas, use the following\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/WalletPasses/PassFields"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3 \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 PassFields}}.\cb1 \

