A table or list can represent data that\'92s organized in groups or hierarchies, and it can support user interactions like selecting, adding, deleting, and reordering. Apps and games in all platforms can use tables to present content and options; many apps use lists to express an overall information hierarchy and help people navigate it. For example, iOS Settings uses a hierarchy of lists to help people choose options, and several apps \'97 such as Mail in iPadOS and macOS \'97 use a table within a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/split-views"}}{\fldrslt \cf12 \ul \ulc12 split view}}.\
Sometimes, people need to work with complex data in a multicolumn table or a spreadsheet. Apps that offer productivity tasks often use a table to represent various characteristics or attributes of the data in separate, sortable columns.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/lists-and-tables#Best-practices"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs56 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Best practices}}
\f0\b\fs56 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Prefer displaying text in a list or table.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  A table can include any type of content, but the row-based format is especially well suited to making text easy to scan and read. If you have items that vary widely in size \'97 or you need to display a large number of images \'97 consider using a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/collections"}}{\fldrslt \cf12 \ul \ulc12 collection}} instead.\

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Let people edit a table when it makes sense.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  People appreciate being able to reorder a list, even if they can\'92t add or remove items. In iOS and iPadOS, people must enter an edit mode before they can select table items.\

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Provide appropriate feedback when people select a list item.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  The feedback can vary depending on whether selecting the item reveals a new view or toggles the item\'92s state. In general, a table that helps people navigate through a hierarchy persistently highlights the selected row to clarify the path people are taking. In contrast, a table that lists options often highlights a row only briefly before adding an image \'97 such as a checkmark \'97 indicating that the item is selected.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/lists-and-tables#Content"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs56 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Content}}
\f0\b\fs56 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Keep item text succinct so row content is comfortable to read.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  Short, succinct text can help minimize truncation and wrapping, making text easier to read and scan. If each item consists of a large amount of text, consider alternatives that help you avoid displaying over-large table rows. For example, you could list item titles only, letting people choose an item to reveal its content in a detail view.\

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Consider ways to preserve readability of text that might otherwise get clipped or truncated.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  When a table is narrow \'97 for example, if people can vary its width \'97 you want content to remain recognizable and easy to read. Sometimes, an ellipsis in the middle of text can make an item easier to distinguish because it preserves both the beginning and the end of the content.\

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Use descriptive column headings in a multicolumn table.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  Use nouns or short noun phrases with {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://support.apple.com/guide/applestyleguide/c-apsgb744e4a3/web#apdca93e113f1d64"}}{\fldrslt \cf12 \ul \ulc12 title-style capitalization}}, and don\'92t add ending punctuation. If you don\'92t include a column heading in a single-column table view, use a label or a header to help people understand the context.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/lists-and-tables#Style"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs56 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Style}}
\f0\b\fs56 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Choose a table or list style that coordinates with your data and platform.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  Some styles use visual details to help communicate grouping and hierarchy or to provide specific experiences. In iOS and iPadOS, for example, the grouped style uses headers, footers, and additional space to separate groups of data; the elliptical style available in watchOS makes items appear as if they\'92re rolling off a rounded surface as people scroll; and macOS defines a bordered style that uses alternating row backgrounds to help make large tables easier to use. For developer guidance, see {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/SwiftUI/ListStyle"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3 \AppleTypeServices \cf12 \ul \ulc12 ListStyle}}.\

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Choose a row style that fits the information you need to display.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  For example, you might need to display a small image in the leading end of a row, followed by a brief explanatory label. Some platforms provide built-in row styles you can use to arrange content in list rows, such as the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/UIKit/UIListContentConfiguration-swift.struct"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3 \AppleTypeServices \cf12 \ul \ulc12 UIListContentConfiguration}} API you can use to lay out content in a list\'92s rows, headers, and footers in iOS, iPadOS, and tvOS.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/lists-and-tables#Platform-considerations"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs56 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Platform considerations}}
\f0\b\fs56 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/lists-and-tables#iOS-iPadOS-visionOS"}}{\fldrslt 
\f5\b0\fs48 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 iOS, iPadOS, visionOS}}
\f5\b0\fs48 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs34 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Use an info button only to reveal more information about a row\'92s content.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  An info button \'97 called a 
\f4\i \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 detail disclosure button
\f1\i0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  when it appears in a list row \'97 doesn\'92t support navigation through a hierarchical table or list. If you need to let people drill into a list or table row\'92s subviews, use a disclosure indicator accessory control. For developer guidance, see {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/UIKit/UITableViewCell/AccessoryType-swift.enum/disclosureIndicator"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3 \AppleTypeServices \cf12 \ul \ulc12 UITableViewCell.AccessoryType.disclosureIndicator}}.\
