\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Avoid adding an index to a table that displays controls \'97 like disclosure indicators \'97 in the trailing ends of its rows.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  An 
\f4\i \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 index
\f1\i0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  typically consists of the letters in an alphabet, displayed vertically at the trailing side of a list. People can jump to a specific section in the list by choosing the index letter that maps to it. Because both the index and elements like disclosure indicators appear on the trailing side of a list, it can be difficult for people to use one element without activating the other.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/lists-and-tables#macOS"}}{\fldrslt 
\f5\fs48 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 macOS}}
\f5\fs48 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs34 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 When it provides value, let people click a column heading to sort a table view based on that column
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 . If people click the heading of a column that\'92s already sorted, re-sort the data in the opposite direction.\

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Let people resize columns.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  Data displayed in a table view often varies in width. People appreciate resizing columns to help them concentrate on different areas or reveal clipped data.\

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Consider using alternating row colors in a multicolumn table.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  Alternating colors can help people track row values across columns, especially in a wide table.\

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Use an outline view instead of a table view to present hierarchical data.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  An {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/outline-views"}}{\fldrslt \cf12 \ul \ulc12 outline view}} looks like a table view, but includes disclosure triangles for exposing nested levels of data. For example, an outline view might display folders and the items they contain.\
