\f0\b\fs80 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Labels\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs56 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 A label is a static piece of text that people can read and often copy, but not edit.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 {{\NeXTGraphic Attachment.png \width320 \height320 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf11 \
Labels display text throughout the interface, in buttons, menu items, and views, helping people understand the current context and what they can do next.\
The term 
\f4\i \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 label
\f1\i0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  refers to uneditable text that can appear in various places. For example:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls9\ilvl0\cf11 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Within a button, a label generally conveys what the button does, such as Edit, Cancel, or Send.\
\ls9\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Within many lists, a label can describe each item, often accompanied by a symbol or an image.\
\ls9\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Within a view, a label might provide additional context by introducing a control or describing a common action or task that people can perform in the view.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf13 \cb14 Developer note\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 \cb14 To display uneditable text, SwiftUI defines two components: {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/SwiftUI/Label"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3 \AppleTypeServices \cf12 \ul \ulc12 Label}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/SwiftUI/Text"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3 \AppleTypeServices \cf12 \ul \ulc12 Text}}.\cf11 \cb1 \
The guidance below can help you use a label to display text. In some cases, guidance for specific components \'97 such as {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/buttons"}}{\fldrslt \cf12 \ul \ulc12 action buttons}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/menus"}}{\fldrslt \cf12 \ul \ulc12 menus}}, and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/lists-and-tables"}}{\fldrslt \cf12 \ul \ulc12 lists and tables}} \'97 includes additional recommendations for using text.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/labels#Best-practices"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs56 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Best practices}}
\f0\b\fs56 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Use a label to display a small amount of text that people don\'92t need to edit.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  If you need to let people edit a small amount of text, use a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/text-fields"}}{\fldrslt \cf12 \ul \ulc12 text field}}. If you need to display a large amount of text, and optionally let people edit it, use a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/text-views"}}{\fldrslt \cf12 \ul \ulc12 text view}}.\

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Prefer system fonts.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  A label can display plain or styled text, and it supports Dynamic Type (where available) by default. If you adjust the style of a label or use custom fonts, make sure the text remains legible.\

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Use system-provided label colors to communicate relative importance.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  The system defines four label colors that vary in appearance to help you give text different levels of visual importance. For additional guidance, see {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/color"}}{\fldrslt \cf12 \ul \ulc12 Color}}.\

