\f0\b\fs80 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cb1 Boxes\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs56 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 A box creates a visually distinct group of logically related information and components.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 {{\NeXTGraphic Attachment.png \width320 \height320 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf11 \
By default, a box uses a visible border or background color to separate its contents from the rest of the interface. A box can also include a title.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/boxes#Best-practices"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs56 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Best practices}}
\f0\b\fs56 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Prefer keeping a box relatively small in comparison with its containing view.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  As a box\'92s size gets close to the size of the containing window or screen, it becomes less effective at communicating the separation of grouped content, and it can crowd other content.\

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Consider using padding and alignment to communicate additional grouping within a box.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  A box\'92s border is a distinct visual element \'97 adding nested boxes to define subgroups can make your interface feel busy and constrained.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/boxes#Content"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs56 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Content}}
\f0\b\fs56 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Provide a succinct introductory title if it helps clarify the box\'92s contents.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  The appearance of a box helps people understand that its contents are related, but it might make sense to provide more detail about the relationship. Also, a title can help VoiceOver users predict the content they encounter within the box.\

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 If you need a title, write a brief phrase that describes the contents.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  Use sentence-style capitalization. Avoid ending punctuation unless you use a box in a settings pane, where you append a colon to the title.\
\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa640\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs80 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 File management\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs56 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Some apps can support documents and files that people expect to manage throughout the system.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 {{\NeXTGraphic Attachment.png \width320 \height320 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf11 \
Document-based apps \'97 such as Pages, Keynote, Photos, and Preview \'97 help people create, edit, and save documents and files, often providing customized ways for people to browse for content they want to open in the app.\
People also expect to browse documents without first opening a document-based app. On a Mac, for example, people use the Finder to access the macOS file system; on iPhone, iPad, and Apple\'a0Vision\'a0Pro, people use the Files app to manage the documents and files on their device. In watchOS and tvOS, people don\'92t typically create, edit, or manage documents, so these systems don\'92t provide a document-browsing interface.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/file-management#Creating-and-opening-files"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs56 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Creating and opening files}}
\f0\b\fs56 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Use app menus and keyboard shortcuts to give people convenient ways to create and open documents.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  In iPadOS and macOS, people expect to create new documents or open existing ones using familiar menu commands. When you provide commands like New or Open, iPadOS presents them in the shortcuts interface that displays when people hold the Command key on a connected hardware keyboard, and macOS presents them in the menu bar File menu. Regardless of the availability of keyboard shortcuts, include an Add (+) button to help people create a new document. In a macOS app, you put the add action in the File menu (for guidance, see {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/the-menu-bar#File-menu"}}{\fldrslt \cf12 \ul \ulc12 File menu}}).\

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 If your app requires a custom file browser, support people\'92s understanding of the platform\'92s file system.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  People who are familiar with the Finder and Files apps already understand the basic layout of their device\'92s file system. Although you might want to show the most relevant part of the file system when your custom file browser opens \'97 for example, a Documents or iCloud folder or the most recently selected location \'97 let people use your browser to view the rest of the file system if they want.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/file-management#Saving-work"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs56 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Saving work}}
\f0\b\fs56 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Help people be confident that their work is always preserved unless they cancel or delete it.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  In general, avoid making people take an explicit action to save their work. Instead, automatically perform periodic saves while they\'92re editing and when they close a file or switch to another app.\

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Hide file extensions by default, but let people view them if they choose.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  Be sure to reflect the current choice in all the save or open interfaces you display.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/file-management#Quick-Look-previews"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs56 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Quick Look previews}}
\f0\b\fs56 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs34 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Quick Look helps you create previews of the files your app handles so that people can view them within your app and in some cases interact with them. For example, you can use Quick Look to let people listen to a preview of an audio file, add markup to a photo\'92s preview, or rotate and scale a 3D file preview to examine it in different ways.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Use a Quick Look viewer to let people preview a file even when your app can\'92t open it.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  If your app lets people attach or otherwise interact with files that it doesn\'92t support, implementing a Quick Look viewer lets people preview those files without leaving your app.\

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Consider implementing a Quick Look generator if your app produces custom file types.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  A Quick Look generator lets other apps \'97 including the Finder, Files, and Spotlight \'97 display previews of your documents, making it easier for people to find them\
\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa640\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs80 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Icons\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs56 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 An effective icon is a graphic asset that expresses a single concept in ways people instantly understand.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 {{\NeXTGraphic Attachment.png \width320 \height320 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf11 \
Apps and games use a variety of simple icons to help people understand the items, actions, and modes they can choose. Unlike {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/app-icons"}}{\fldrslt \cf12 \ul \ulc12 app icons}}, which can use rich visual details like shading, texturing, and highlighting to evoke the app\'92s personality, an 
\f4\i \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 interface icon
\f1\i0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  typically uses streamlined shapes and touches of color to communicate a straightforward idea.\
You can design interface icons \'97 also called 
\f4\i \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 glyphs
\f1\i0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  \'97 or you can choose symbols from the SF Symbols app, using them as-is or customizing them to suit your needs. Both interface icons and symbols use black and clear colors to define their shapes; the system can apply other colors to the black areas in each image. For guidance, see {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/sf-symbols"}}{\fldrslt \cf12 \ul \ulc12 SF Symbols}}.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/icons#Best-practices"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs56 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Best practices}}
\f0\b\fs56 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Create a recognizable, highly simplified design.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  Too many details can make an interface icon confusing or unreadable. Strive for a simple, universal design that most people will recognize quickly. In general, icons work best when they use familiar visual metaphors that are directly related to the actions they initiate or content they represent.\

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Maintain visual consistency across all interface icons in your app.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  Whether you use only custom icons or mix custom and system-provided ones, all interface icons in your app need to use a consistent size, level of detail, stroke thickness (or weight), and perspective. Depending on the visual weight of an icon, you may need to adjust its dimensions to ensure that it appears visually consistent with other icons.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf11 {{\NeXTGraphic Attachment.png \width320 \height320 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf11 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 To help achieve visual consistency, adjust individual icon sizes as necessary\'85\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf11 {{\NeXTGraphic Attachment.png \width320 \height320 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf11 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 \'85and use the same stroke weight in every icon.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 In general, match the weights of interface icons and adjacent text.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  Unless you want to emphasize either the icons or the text, using the same weight for both gives your content a consistent appearance and level of emphasis.\

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 If necessary, add padding to a custom interface icon to achieve optical alignment.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  Some icons \'97 especially asymmetric ones \'97 can look unbalanced when you center them geometrically instead of optically. For example, the download icon shown below has more visual weight on the bottom than on the top, which can make it look too low if it\'92s geometrically centered.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf11 {{\NeXTGraphic Attachment.png \width320 \height320 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf11 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 An asymmetric icon can look off center even though it\'92s not.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 \
In such cases, you can slightly adjust the position of the icon until it\'92s optically centered. When you create an asset that includes your adjustments as padding around an interface icon (as shown below on the right), you can optically center the icon by geometrically centering the asset.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf11 {{\NeXTGraphic Attachment.png \width320 \height320 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf11 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Moving the icon a few pixels higher optically centers it; including the pixels in padding simplifies centering.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 \
Adjustments for optical centering are typically very small, but they can have a big impact on your app\'92s appearance.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf11 {{\NeXTGraphic Attachment.png \width320 \height320 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf11 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Before optical centering (left) and after optical centering (right).\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Provide a selected-state version of an interface icon only if necessary.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  You don\'92t need to provide selected and unselected appearances for an icon that\'92s used in standard system components such as toolbars, tab bars, and buttons. The system updates the visual appearance of the selected state automatically.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf11 {{\NeXTGraphic Attachment.png \width320 \height320 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf11 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 In a toolbar, a selected icon receives the app\'92s accent color.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

