\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 If you create a custom interface icon, use a vector format like PDF or SVG.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  The system automatically scales a vector-based interface icon for high-resolution displays, so you don\'92t need to provide high-resolution versions of it. In contrast, PNG \'97 used for app icons and other images that include effects like shading, textures, and highlighting \'97 doesn\'92t support scaling, so you have to supply multiple versions for each PNG-based interface icon. Alternatively, you can create a custom SF Symbol and specify a scale that ensures the symbol\'92s emphasis matches adjacent text. For guidance, see {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/sf-symbols"}}{\fldrslt \cf12 \ul \ulc12 SF Symbols}}.\

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Provide alternative text labels for custom interface icons.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  Alternative text labels \'97 or accessibility descriptions \'97 aren\'92t visible, but they let VoiceOver audibly describe what\'92s onscreen, simplifying navigation for people with visual disabilities. For guidance, see {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/voiceover"}}{\fldrslt \cf12 \ul \ulc12 VoiceOver}}.\

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Avoid using replicas of Apple hardware products.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  Hardware designs tend to change frequently and can make your interface icons and other content appear dated. If you must display Apple hardware, use only the images available in {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/resources/"}}{\fldrslt \cf12 \ul \ulc12 Apple Design Resources}} or the SF Symbols that represent various Apple products.\
