\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 In general, avoid light font weights.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  For example, if you\'92re using system-provided fonts, prefer Regular, Medium, Semibold, or Bold font weights, and avoid Ultralight, Thin, and Light font weights, which can be difficult to see, especially when text is small.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/typography#Conveying-hierarchy"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs56 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Conveying hierarchy}}
\f0\b\fs56 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Adjust font weight, size, and color as needed to emphasize important information and help people visualize hierarchy.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  Be sure to maintain the relative hierarchy and visual distinction of text elements when people adjust text sizes.\

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Minimize the number of typefaces you use, even in a highly customized interface.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  Mixing too many different typefaces can obscure your information hierarchy and hinder readability, in addition to making an interface feel internally inconsistent or poorly designed.\

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Prioritize important content when responding to text-size changes.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  Not all content is equally important. When someone chooses a larger text size, they typically want to make the content they care about easier to read; they don\'92t always want to increase the size of every word on the screen. For example, when people increase text size to read the content in a tabbed window, they don\'92t expect the tab titles to increase in size. Similarly, in a game, people are often more interested in a character\'92s dialog than in transient hit-damage values.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/typography#Using-system-fonts"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs56 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Using system fonts}}
\f0\b\fs56 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs34 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Apple provides two typeface families that support an extensive range of weights, sizes, styles, and languages.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 San Francisco (SF)
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  is a sans serif typeface family that includes the SF Pro, SF Compact, SF Arabic, SF Armenian, SF Georgian, SF Hebrew, and SF Mono variants.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf11 {{\NeXTGraphic Attachment.png \width320 \height320 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf11 \
The system also offers SF Pro, SF Compact, SF Arabic, SF Armenian, SF Georgian, and SF Hebrew in rounded variants you can use to coordinate text with the appearance of soft or rounded UI elements, or to provide an alternative typographic voice.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 New York (NY)
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  is a serif typeface family designed to work well by itself and alongside the SF fonts.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf11 {{\NeXTGraphic Attachment.png \width320 \height320 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf11 \
You can download the San Francisco and New York fonts {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/fonts/"}}{\fldrslt \cf12 \ul \ulc12 here}}.\
The system provides the SF and NY fonts in the 
\f4\i \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 variable
\f1\i0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  font format, which combines different font styles together in one file, and supports interpolation between styles to create intermediate ones.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf13 \cb14 Note\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 \cb14 Variable fonts support 
\f4\i \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 \cb14 optical sizing
\f1\i0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 \cb14 , which refers to the adjustment of different typographic designs to fit different sizes. On all platforms, the system fonts support 
\f4\i \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 \cb14 dynamic optical sizes
\f1\i0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 \cb14 , which merge discrete optical sizes (like Text and Display) and weights into a single, continuous design, letting the system interpolate each glyph or letterform to produce a structure that\'92s precisely adapted to the point size. With dynamic optical sizes, you don\'92t need to use discrete optical sizes unless you\'92re working with a design tool that doesn\'92t support all the features of the variable font format.\cf11 \cb1 \
To help you define visual hierarchies and create clear and legible designs in many different sizes and contexts, the system fonts are available in a variety of weights, ranging from Ultralight to Black, and \'97 in the case of SF \'97 several widths, including Condensed and Expanded. Because SF Symbols use equivalent weights, you can achieve precise weight matching between symbols and adjacent text, regardless of the size or style you choose.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf11 {{\NeXTGraphic Attachment.png \width320 \height320 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf11 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf13 \cb14 Note\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/sf-symbols"}}{\fldrslt 
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf12 \cb14 \ul \ulc12 SF Symbols}}
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 \cb14  provides a comprehensive library of symbols that integrate seamlessly with the San Francisco system font, automatically aligning with text in all weights and sizes. Consider using symbols when you need to convey a concept or depict an object, especially within text.\cf11 \cb1 \
The system defines a set of typographic attributes \'97 called text styles \'97 that work with both typeface families. A 
\f4\i \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 text style
\f1\i0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  specifies a combination of font weight, point size, and leading values for each text size. For example, the 
\f4\i \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 body
\f1\i0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  text style uses values that support a comfortable reading experience over multiple lines of text, while the 
\f4\i \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 headline
\f1\i0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  style assigns a font size and weight that help distinguish a heading from surrounding content. Taken together, the text styles form a typographic hierarchy you can use to express the different levels of importance in your content. Text styles also allow text to scale proportionately when people change the system\'92s text size or make accessibility adjustments, like turning on Larger Text in Accessibility settings.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Consider using the built-in text styles.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  The system-defined text styles give you a convenient and consistent way to convey your information hierarchy through font size and weight. Using text styles with the system fonts also ensures support for Dynamic Type and larger accessibility type sizes (where available), which let people choose the text size that works for them. For guidance, see {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/typography#Supporting-Dynamic-Type"}}{\fldrslt \cf12 \ul \ulc12 Supporting Dynamic Type}}.\

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Modify the built-in text styles if necessary.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  System APIs define font adjustments \'97 called 
\f4\i \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 symbolic traits
\f1\i0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  \'97 that let you modify some aspects of a text style. For example, the bold trait adds weight to text, letting you create another level of hierarchy. You can also use symbolic traits to adjust leading if you need to improve readability or conserve space. For example, when you display text in wide columns or long passages, more space between lines (
\f4\i \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 loose leading
\f1\i0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 ) can make it easier for people to keep their place while moving from one line to the next. Conversely, if you need to display multiple lines of text in an area where height is constrained \'97 for example, in a list row \'97 decreasing the space between lines (
\f4\i \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 tight leading
\f1\i0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 ) can help the text fit well. If you need to display three or more lines of text, avoid tight leading even in areas where height is limited. For developer guidance, see {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/SwiftUI/Font/leading(_:)"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3 \AppleTypeServices \cf12 \ul \ulc12 leading(_:)}}.\
