\fs34 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 \
For a list of available Dynamic Type sizes, see {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/typography#Specifications"}}{\fldrslt \cf12 \ul \ulc12 Specifications}}. You can also download Dynamic Type size tables in the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/resources/"}}{\fldrslt \cf12 \ul \ulc12 Apple Design Resources}} for each platform.\
For developer guidance, see {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/SwiftUI/Text-input-and-output"}}{\fldrslt \cf12 \ul \ulc12 Text input and output}}. To support Dynamic Type in Unity-based games, use {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/apple/unityplugins"}}{\fldrslt \cf12 \ul \ulc12 Apple\'92s Unity plug-ins}}.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Make sure your app\'92s layout adapts to all font sizes.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  Verify that your design scales, and that text and glyphs are legible at all font sizes. On iPhone or iPad, turn on Larger Accessibility Text Sizes in Settings > Accessibility > Display & Text Size > Larger Text, and confirm that your app remains comfortably readable.\

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Increase the size of meaningful interface icons as font size increases.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  If you use interface icons to communicate important information, make sure they\'92re easy to view at larger font sizes too. When you use {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/sf-symbols"}}{\fldrslt \cf12 \ul \ulc12 SF Symbols}}, you get icons that scale automatically with Dynamic Type size changes.\

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Keep text truncation to a minimum as font size increases.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  In general, aim to display as much useful text at the largest accessibility font size as you do at the largest standard font size. Avoid truncating text in scrollable regions unless people can open a separate view to read the rest of the content. You can prevent text truncation in a label by configuring it to use as many lines as needed to display a useful amount of text. For developer guidance, see {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/UIKit/UILabel/numberOfLines"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3 \AppleTypeServices \cf12 \ul \ulc12 numberOfLines}}.\

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Consider adjusting your layout at large font sizes.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  When font size increases in a horizontally constrained context, inline items (like glyphs and timestamps) and container boundaries can crowd text and cause truncation or overlapping. To improve readability, consider using a stacked layout where text appears above secondary items. Multicolumn text can also be less readable at large sizes due to horizontal space constraints. Reduce the number of columns when the font size increases to avoid truncation and enhance readability. For developer guidance, see {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/UIKit/UIContentSizeCategory/isAccessibilityCategory"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3 \AppleTypeServices \cf12 \ul \ulc12 isAccessibilityCategory}}.\

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Maintain a consistent information hierarchy regardless of the current font size.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  For example, keep primary elements toward the top of a view even when the font size is very large, so that people don\'92t lose track of these elements.\
