\f0\b\fs80 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Materials\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs56 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 A material is a visual effect that creates a sense of depth, layering, and hierarchy between foreground and background elements.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 {{\NeXTGraphic Attachment.png \width320 \height320 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf11 \
Materials help visually separate foreground elements, such as text and controls, from background elements, such as content and solid colors. By allowing color to pass through from background to foreground, a material establishes visual hierarchy to help people more easily retain a sense of place.\
Apple platforms feature two types of materials: Liquid Glass, and standard materials. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/materials#Liquid-Glass"}}{\fldrslt \cf12 \ul \ulc12 Liquid Glass}} is a dynamic material that unifies the design language across Apple platforms, allowing you to present controls and navigation without obscuring underlying content. In contrast to Liquid Glass, the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/materials#Standard-materials"}}{\fldrslt \cf12 \ul \ulc12 standard materials}} help with visual differentiation within the content layer.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/materials#Liquid-Glass"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs56 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Liquid Glass}}
\f0\b\fs56 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs34 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Liquid Glass forms a distinct functional layer for controls and navigation elements \'97 like tab bars and sidebars \'97 that floats above the content layer, establishing a clear visual hierarchy between functional elements and content. Liquid Glass allows content to scroll and peek through from beneath these elements to give the interface a sense of dynamism and depth, all while maintaining legibility for controls and navigation.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf11 Don\'92t use Liquid Glass in the content layer.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  Liquid Glass works best when it provides a clear distinction between interactive elements and content, and including it in the content layer can result in unnecessary complexity and a confusing visual hierarchy. Instead, use {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/materials#Standard-materials"}}{\fldrslt \cf12 \ul \ulc12 standard materials}} for elements in the content layer, such as app backgrounds. An exception to this is for controls in the content layer with a transient interactive element like {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/sliders"}}{\fldrslt \cf12 \ul \ulc12 sliders}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/toggles"}}{\fldrslt \cf12 \ul \ulc12 toggles}}; in these cases, the element takes on a Liquid Glass appearance to emphasize its interactivity when a person activates it.\

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Use Liquid Glass effects sparingly.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  Standard components from system frameworks pick up the appearance and behavior of this material automatically. If you apply Liquid Glass effects to a custom control, do so sparingly. Liquid Glass seeks to bring attention to the underlying content, and overusing this material in multiple custom controls can provide a subpar user experience by distracting from that content. Limit these effects to the most important functional elements in your app. For developer guidance, see {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/SwiftUI/Applying-Liquid-Glass-to-custom-views"}}{\fldrslt \cf12 \ul \ulc12 Applying Liquid Glass to custom views}}.\

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Only use clear Liquid Glass for components that appear over visually rich backgrounds.
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  Liquid Glass provides two variants \'97 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/SwiftUI/Glass/regular"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3 \AppleTypeServices \cf12 \ul \ulc12 regular}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/SwiftUI/Glass/clear"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3 \AppleTypeServices \cf12 \ul \ulc12 clear}} \'97 that you can choose when building custom components or styling some system components. The appearance of these variants can differ in response to certain system settings, like if people choose a preferred look for Liquid Glass in their device\'92s display settings, or turn on accessibility settings that reduce transparency or increase contrast in the interface.\
The 
\f4\i \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 regular
\f1\i0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  variant blurs and adjusts the luminosity of background content to maintain legibility of text and other foreground elements. Scroll edge effects further enhance legibility by blurring and reducing the opacity of background content. Most system components use this variant. Use the regular variant when background content might create legibility issues, or when components have a significant amount of text, such as alerts, sidebars, or popovers.\
\
