\AppleTypeServices \cf2 \cb3 \outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Labels display text throughout the interface, in buttons, menu items, and views, helping people understand the current context and what they can do next.\
The term\'a0
\f4\i label
\f1\i0 \'a0refers to uneditable text that can appear in various places. For example:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls14\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Within a button, a label generally conveys what the button does, such as Edit, Cancel, or Send.\cb1 \
\ls14\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Within many lists, a label can describe each item, often accompanied by a symbol or an image.\cb1 \
\ls14\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Within a view, a label might provide additional context by introducing a control or describing a common action or task that people can perform in the view.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf9 \cb10 \strokec9 Developer note\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \cb10 \strokec2 To display uneditable text, SwiftUI defines two components:\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/SwiftUI/Label"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3 \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Label}}\'a0and\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/SwiftUI/Text"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3 \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Text}}.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 The guidance below can help you use a label to display text. In some cases, guidance for specific components \'97 such as\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/buttons"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 action buttons}},\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/menus"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 menus}}, and\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/lists-and-tables"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 lists and tables}}\'a0\'97 includes additional recommendations for using text.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/labels#Best-practices"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 Best practices}}
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs34 \cf2 Use a label to display a small amount of text that people don\'92t need to edit.
\f1\b0 \'a0If you need to let people edit a small amount of text, use a\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/text-fields"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 text field}}. If you need to display a large amount of text, and optionally let people edit it, use a\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/text-views"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 text view}}.\

\f2\b Prefer system fonts.
\f1\b0 \'a0A label can display plain or styled text, and it supports Dynamic Type (where available) by default. If you adjust the style of a label or use custom fonts, make sure the text remains legible.\

\f2\b Use system-provided label colors to communicate relative importance.
\f1\b0 \'a0The system defines four label colors that vary in appearance to help you give text different levels of visual importance. For additional guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/color"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Color}}.\

