\f0\b\fs67\fsmilli33882 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Outline views\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs39\fsmilli19765 \cf2 \cb3 An outline view presents hierarchical data in a scrolling list of cells that are organized into columns and rows.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \strokec2 {{\NeXTGraphic Attachment.png \width320 \height320 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 An outline view includes at least one column that contains primary hierarchical data, such as a set of parent containers and their children. You can add columns, as needed, to display attributes that supplement the primary data; for example, sizes and modification dates. Parent containers have disclosure triangles that expand to reveal their children.\cb1 \
\cb3 Finder windows offer an outline view for navigating the file system.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/outline-views#Best-practices"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Best practices}}
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Outline views work well to display text-based content and often appear in the leading side of a\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/split-views"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 split view}}, with related content on the opposite side.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Use a table instead of an outline view to present data that\'92s not hierarchical.
\f1\b0 \'a0For guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/lists-and-tables"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Lists and tables}}.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Expose data hierarchy in the first column only.
\f1\b0 \'a0Other columns can display attributes that apply to the hierarchical data in the primary column.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Use descriptive column headings to provide context.
\f1\b0 \'a0Use nouns or short noun phrases with\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://help.apple.com/applestyleguide/#/apsgb744e4a3?sub=apdca93e113f1d64"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 title-style capitalization}}\'a0and no punctuation; in particular, avoid adding a trailing colon. Always provide column headings in a multi-column outline view. If you don\'92t include a column heading in a single-column outline view, use a label or other means to make sure there\'92s enough context.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Consider letting people click column headings to sort an outline view.
\f1\b0 \'a0In a sortable outline view, people can click a column heading to perform an ascending or descending sort based on that column. You can implement additional sorting based on secondary columns behind the scenes, if necessary. If people click the primary column heading, sorting occurs at each hierarchy level. For example, in the Finder, all top-level folders are sorted, then the items within each folder are sorted. If people click the heading of a column that\'92s already sorted, the folders and their contents are sorted again in the opposite direction.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Let people resize columns.
\f1\b0 \'a0Data displayed in an outline view often varies in width. It\'92s important to let people adjust column width as needed to reveal data that\'92s wider than the column.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Make it easy for people to expand or collapse nested containers.
\f1\b0 \'a0For example, clicking a disclosure triangle for a folder in a Finder window expands only that folder. However, Option-clicking the disclosure triangle expands all of its subfolders.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Retain people\'92s expansion choices.
\f1\b0 \'a0If people expand various levels of an outline view to reach a specific item, store the state so you can display it again the next time. This way, people won\'92t need to navigate back to the same place again.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Consider using alternating row colors in multi-column outline views.
\f1\b0 \'a0Alternating colors can make it easier for people to track row values across columns, especially in wide outline views.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Let people edit data if it makes sense in your app.
\f1\b0 \'a0In an editable outline view cell, people expect to be able to single-click a cell to edit its contents. Note that a cell can respond differently to a double click. For example, an outline view listing files might let people single-click a file\'92s name to edit it, but double-click a file\'92s name to open the file. You can also let people reorder, add, and remove rows if it would be useful.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Consider using a centered ellipsis to truncate cell text instead of clipping it.
\f1\b0 \'a0An ellipsis in the middle preserves the beginning and end of the cell text, which can make the content more distinct and recognizable than clipped text.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Consider offering a search field to help people find values quickly in a lengthy outline view.
\f1\b0 \'a0Windows with an outline view as the primary feature often include a search field in the toolbar. For guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/search-fields"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Search fields}}.\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs39\fsmilli19765 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 A tab view presents multiple mutually exclusive panes of content in the same area, which people can switch between using a tabbed control.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \strokec2 {{\NeXTGraphic Attachment.png \width320 \height320 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/tab-views#Best-practices"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Best practices}}
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Use a tab view to present closely related areas of content.
\f1\b0 \'a0The appearance of a tab view provides a strong visual indication of enclosure. People expect each tab to display content that is in some way similar or related to the content in the other tabs.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Make sure the controls within a pane affect content only in the same pane.
\f1\b0 \'a0Panes are mutually exclusive, so ensure they\'92re fully self-contained.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Provide a label for each tab that describes the contents of its pane.
\f1\b0 \'a0A good label helps people predict the contents of a pane before clicking or tapping its tab. In general, use nouns or short noun phrases for tab labels. A verb or short verb phrase may make sense in some contexts. Use title-style capitalization for tab labels.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Avoid using a pop-up button to switch between tabs.
\f1\b0 \'a0A tabbed control is efficient because it requires a single click or tap to make a selection, whereas a pop-up button requires two. A tabbed control also presents all choices onscreen at the same time, whereas people must click a pop-up button to see its choices. Note that a pop-up button can be a reasonable alternative in cases where there are too many panes of content to reasonably display with tabs.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Avoid providing more than six tabs in a tab view.
\f1\b0 \'a0Having more than six tabs can be overwhelming and create layout issues. If you need to present six or more tabs, consider another way to implement the interface. For example, you could instead present each tab as a view option in a pop-up button menu.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 For developer guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/AppKit/NSTabView"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3 \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 NSTabView}}.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/tab-views#Anatomy"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Anatomy}}
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 The tabbed control appears on the top edge of the content area. You can choose to hide the control, which is appropriate for an app that switches between panes programmatically.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 {{\NeXTGraphic Attachment.png \width320 \height320 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 When you hide the tabbed control, the content area can be borderless, bezeled, or bordered with a line. A borderless view can be solid or transparent.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 In general, inset a tab view by leaving a margin of window-body area on all sides of a tab view.
\f1\b0 \'a0This layout looks clean and leaves room for additional controls that aren\'92t directly related to the contents of the tab view. You can extend a tab view to meet the window edges, but this layout is unusual.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs39\fsmilli19765 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 A button initiates an instantaneous action.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \strokec2 {{\NeXTGraphic Attachment.png \width320 \height320 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 Versatile and highly customizable, buttons give people simple, familiar ways to do tasks in your app. In general, a button combines three attributes to clearly communicate its function:\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls15\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Style.
\f1\b0 \'a0A visual style based on size, color, and shape.\cb1 \
\ls15\ilvl0
\f2\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Content.
\f1\b0 \'a0A symbol (or icon), text label, or both that a button displays to convey its purpose.\cb1 \
\ls15\ilvl0
\f2\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Role.
\f1\b0 \'a0A system-defined role that identifies a button\'92s semantic meaning and can affect its appearance.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 There are also many button-like components that have distinct appearances and behaviors for specific use cases, like\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/toggles"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 toggles}},\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/pop-up-buttons"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 pop-up buttons}}, and\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/segmented-controls"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 segmented controls}}.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/buttons#Best-practices"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Best practices}}
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 When buttons are instantly recognizable and easy to understand, an app tends to feel intuitive and well designed.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Make buttons easy for people to use.
\f1\b0 \'a0It\'92s essential to include enough space around a button so that people can visually distinguish it from surrounding components and content. Giving a button enough space is also critical for helping people select or activate it, regardless of the method of input they use. As a general rule, a button needs a hit region of at least 44x44 pt \'97 in visionOS, 60x60 pt \'97 to ensure that people can select it easily, whether they use a fingertip, a pointer, their eyes, or a remote.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Always include a press state for a custom button.
\f1\b0 \'a0Without a press state, a button can feel unresponsive, making people wonder if it\'92s accepting their input.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/buttons#Style"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Style}}
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 System buttons offer a range of styles that support customization while providing built-in interaction states, accessibility support, and appearance adaptation. Different platforms define different styles that help you communicate hierarchies of actions in your app.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 In general, use a button that has a prominent visual style for the most likely action in a view.
\f1\b0 \'a0To draw people\'92s attention to a specific button, use a prominent button style so the system can apply an accent color to the button\'92s background. Buttons that use color tend to be the most visually distinctive, helping people quickly identify the actions they\'92re most likely to use. Keep the number of prominent buttons to one or two per view. Presenting too many prominent buttons increases cognitive load, requiring people to spend more time considering options before making a choice.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Use style \'97 not size \'97 to visually distinguish the preferred choice among multiple options.
\f1\b0 \'a0When you use buttons of the same size to offer two or more options, you signal that the options form a coherent set of choices. By contrast, placing two buttons of different sizes near each other can make the interface look confusing and inconsistent. If you want to highlight the preferred or most likely option in a set, use a more prominent button style for that option and a less prominent style for the remaining ones.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Avoid applying a similar color to button labels and content layer backgrounds.
\f1\b0 \'a0If your app already has bright, colorful content in the content layer, prefer using the default monochromatic appearance of button labels. For more guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/color#Liquid-Glass-color"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Liquid Glass color}}.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/buttons#Content"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Content}}
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Ensure that each button clearly communicates its purpose.
\f1\b0 \'a0Depending on the platform, a button can contain a symbol (or icon), a text label, or both to help people understand what it does.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf9 \cb10 \strokec9 Note\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \cb10 \strokec2 In macOS and visionOS, the system displays a tooltip after people hover over a button for a moment. A tooltip displays a brief phrase that explains what a button does; for guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/offering-help"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb10 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Offering help}}.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Try to associate familiar actions with familiar icons.
\f1\b0 \'a0For example, people can predict that a button containing the\'a0
\f3 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 square.and.arrow.up
\f1 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 \'a0symbol will help them perform share-related activities. If it makes sense to use an icon in your button, consider using an existing or customized\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/sf-symbols"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 symbol}}. For a list of symbols that represent common actions, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/icons#Standard-icons"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Standard icons}}.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Consider using text when a short label communicates more clearly than an icon.
\f1\b0 \'a0To use text, write a few words that succinctly describe what the button does. Using\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://help.apple.com/applestyleguide/#/apsgb744e4a3?sub=apdca93e113f1d64"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 title-style capitalization}}, consider starting the label with a verb to help convey the button\'92s action \'97 for example, a button that lets people add items to their shopping cart might use the label \'93Add to Cart.\'94\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/buttons#Role"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Role}}
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 A system button can have one of the following roles:\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls16\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Normal.
\f1\b0 \'a0No specific meaning.\cb1 \
\ls16\ilvl0
\f2\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Primary.
\f1\b0 \'a0The button is the default button \'97 the button people are most likely to choose.\cb1 \
\ls16\ilvl0
\f2\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Cancel.
\f1\b0 \'a0The button cancels the current action.\cb1 \
\ls16\ilvl0
\f2\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Destructive.
\f1\b0 \'a0The button performs an action that can result in data destruction.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 A button\'92s role can have additional effects on its appearance. For example, a primary button uses an app\'92s accent color, whereas a destructive button uses the system red color.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 {{\NeXTGraphic Attachment.png \width320 \height320 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Assign the primary role to the button people are most likely to choose.
\f1\b0 \'a0When a primary button responds to the Return key, it makes it easy for people to quickly confirm their choice. In addition, when the button is in a temporary view \'97 like a\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/sheets"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 sheet}}, an editable view, or an\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/alerts"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 alert}}\'a0\'97 assigning it the primary role means that the view can automatically close when people press Return.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Don\'92t assign the primary role to a button that performs a destructive action, even if that action is the most likely choice.
\f1\b0 \'a0Because of its visual prominence, people sometimes choose a primary button without reading it first. Help people avoid losing content by assigning the primary role to nondestructive buttons.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/buttons#Platform-considerations"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Platform considerations}}
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f4\i\b0\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 No additional considerations for tvOS.
\f1\i0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/buttons#iOS-iPadOS"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs39\fsmilli19765 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 iOS, iPadOS}}
\fs39\fsmilli19765 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Configure a button to display an activity indicator when you need to provide feedback about an action that doesn\'92t instantly complete.
\f1\b0 \'a0Displaying an activity indicator within a button can save space in your user interface while clearly communicating the reason for the delay. To help clarify what\'92s happening, you can also configure the button to display a different label alongside the activity indicator. For example, the label \'93Checkout\'94 could change to \'93Checking out\'85\'94 while the activity indicator is visible. When a delay occurs after people click or tap your configured button, the system displays the activity indicator next to the original or alternative label, hiding the button image, if there is one.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 {{\NeXTGraphic Attachment.png \width320 \height320 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 {{\NeXTGraphic Attachment.png \width320 \height320 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/buttons#macOS"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs39\fsmilli19765 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 macOS}}
\fs39\fsmilli19765 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Several specific button types are unique to macOS.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/buttons#Push-buttons"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs33\fsmilli16941 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Push buttons}}
\fs33\fsmilli16941 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 The standard button type in macOS is known as a\'a0
\f4\i push button
\f1\i0 . You can configure a push button to display text, a symbol, an icon, or an image, or a combination of text and image content. Push buttons can act as the default button in a view and you can tint them.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Use a flexible-height push button only when you need to display tall or variable height content.
\f1\b0 \'a0Flexible-height buttons support the same configurations as regular push buttons \'97 and they use the same corner radius and content padding \'97 so they look consistent with other buttons in your interface. If you need to present a button that contains two lines of text or a tall icon, use a flexible-height button; otherwise, use a standard push button. For developer guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/AppKit/NSButton/BezelStyle-swift.enum/flexiblePush"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3 \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 NSButton.BezelStyle.flexiblePush}}.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Append a trailing ellipsis to the title when a push button opens another window, view, or app.
\f1\b0 \'a0Throughout the system, an ellipsis in a control title signals that people can provide additional input. For example, the Edit buttons in the AutoFill pane of Safari Settings include ellipses because they open other views that let people modify autofill values.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Consider supporting spring loading.
\f1\b0 \'a0On systems with a Magic Trackpad,\'a0
\f4\i spring loading
\f1\i0 \'a0lets people activate a button by dragging selected items over it and force clicking \'97 that is, pressing harder \'97 without dropping the selected items. After force clicking, people can continue dragging the items, possibly to perform additional actions.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/buttons#Square-buttons"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs33\fsmilli16941 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Square buttons}}
\fs33\fsmilli16941 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 A\'a0
\f4\i square button
\f1\i0 \'a0(also known as a\'a0
\f4\i gradient button
\f1\i0 ) initiates an action related to a view, like adding or removing rows in a table.\cb1 \
\cb3 Square buttons contain symbols or icons \'97 not text \'97 and you can configure them to behave like push buttons, toggles, or pop-up buttons. The buttons appear in close proximity to their associated view \'97 usually within or beneath it \'97 so people know which view the buttons affect.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Use square buttons in a view, not in the window frame.
\f1\b0 \'a0Square buttons aren\'92t intended for use in toolbars or status bars. If you need a button in a\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/toolbars"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 toolbar}}, use a toolbar item.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Prefer using a symbol in a square button.
\f1\b0 \'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/sf-symbols"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 SF Symbols}}\'a0provides a wide range of symbols that automatically receive appropriate coloring in their default state and in response to user interaction.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Avoid using labels to introduce square buttons.
\f1\b0 \'a0Because square buttons are closely connected with a specific view, their purpose is generally clear without the need for descriptive text.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 For developer guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/AppKit/NSButton/BezelStyle-swift.enum/smallSquare"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3 \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 NSButton.BezelStyle.smallSquare}}.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/buttons#Help-buttons"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs33\fsmilli16941 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Help buttons}}
\fs33\fsmilli16941 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 A\'a0
\f4\i help button
\f1\i0 \'a0appears within a view and opens app-specific help documentation.\cb1 \
\cb3 Help buttons are circular, consistently sized buttons that contain a question mark. For guidance on creating help documentation, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/offering-help"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Offering help}}.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Use the system-provided help button to display your help documentation.
\f1\b0 \'a0People are familiar with the appearance of the standard help button and know that choosing it opens help content.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 When possible, open the help topic that\'92s related to the current context.
\f1\b0 \'a0For example, the help button in the Rules pane of Mail settings opens the Mail User Guide to a help topic that explains how to change these settings. If no specific help topic applies directly to the current context, open the top level of your app\'92s help documentation when people choose a help button.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Include no more than one help button per window.
\f1\b0 \'a0Multiple help buttons in the same context make it hard for people to predict the result of clicking one.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Position help buttons where people expect to find them.
\f1\b0 \'a0Use the following locations for guidance.\cb1 \

