\f2\b\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Use a help button within a view, not in the window frame.
\f1\b0 \'a0For example, avoid placing a help button in a toolbar or status bar.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Avoid displaying text that introduces a help button.
\f1\b0 \'a0People know what a help button does, so they don\'92t need additional descriptive text.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/buttons#Image-buttons"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs33\fsmilli16941 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Image buttons}}
\fs33\fsmilli16941 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 An\'a0
\f4\i image button
\f1\i0 \'a0appears in a view and displays an image, symbol, or icon. You can configure an image button to behave like a push button, toggle, or pop-up button.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Use an image button in a view, not in the window frame.
\f1\b0 \'a0For example, avoid placing an image button in a toolbar or status bar. If you need to use an image as a button in a toolbar, use a toolbar item. See\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/toolbars"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Toolbars}}.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Include about 10 pixels of padding between the edges of the image and the button edges.
\f1\b0 \'a0An image button\'92s edges define its clickable area even when they aren\'92t visible. Including padding ensures that a click registers correctly even if it\'92s not precisely within the image. In general, avoid including a system-provided border in an image button; for developer guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/AppKit/NSButton/isBordered"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3 \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 isBordered}}.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 If you need to include a label, position it below the image button.
\f1\b0 \'a0For related guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/labels"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Labels}}.\cb1 \
\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa640\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs67\fsmilli33882 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Menus\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs39\fsmilli19765 \cf2 \cb3 A menu reveals its options when people interact with it, making it a space-efficient way to present commands in your app or game.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \strokec2 {{\NeXTGraphic Attachment.png \width320 \height320 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 Menus are ubiquitous in apps and games, so most people already know how to use them. Whether you use system-provided components or custom ones, people expect menus to behave in familiar ways. For example, people understand that opening a menu reveals one or more\'a0
\f4\i menu items
\f1\i0 , each of which represents a command, option, or state that affects the current selection or context. The guidance for labeling and organizing menu items applies to all types of menus in all experiences.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf9 \cb10 \strokec9 Note\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \cb10 \strokec2 Several system-provided components also include menus that support specific use cases. For example, a\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/pop-up-buttons"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb10 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 pop-up button}}\'a0or\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/pull-down-buttons"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb10 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 pull-down button}}\'a0can reveal a menu of options directly related to its action; a\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/context-menus"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb10 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 context menu}}\'a0lets people access a small number of frequently used actions relevant to their current view or task; and in macOS and iPadOS,\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/the-menu-bar"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb10 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 menu bar}}\'a0menus contain all the commands people can perform in the app or game.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/menus#Labels"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Labels}}
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 A menu item\'92s label describes what it does and may include a symbol if it helps to clarify meaning. In an app, a menu item can also display the associated keyboard command, if there is one; in a game, a menu item rarely displays a keyboard command because a game typically needs to handle input from a wider range of devices and may offer game-specific mappings for various keys.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf9 \cb10 \strokec9 Note\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \cb10 \strokec2 Depending on menu layout, an iOS, iPadOS, or visionOS app can display a few unlabeled menu items that use only symbols or icons to identify them. For guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/menus#visionOS"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb10 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 visionOS}}\'a0and\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/menus#iOS-iPadOS"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb10 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 iOS, iPadOS}}.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 For each menu item, write a label that clearly and succinctly describes it.
\f1\b0 \'a0In general, label a menu item that initiates an action using a verb or verb phrase that describes the action, such as View, Close, or Select. For guidance labeling menu items that show and hide something in the interface or show the currently selected state of something, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/menus#Toggled-items"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Toggled items}}. As with all the copy you write, let your app\'92s or game\'92s communication style guide the tone of the menu-item labels you create.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 To be consistent with platform experiences, use title-style capitalization.
\f1\b0 \'a0Although a game might have a different writing style, generally prefer using title-style capitalization, which capitalizes every word except articles, coordinating conjunctions, and short prepositions, and capitalizes the last word in the label, regardless of the part of speech. For complete guidance on this style of capitalization in English, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://support.apple.com/guide/applestyleguide/c-apsgb744e4a3/web#apdca93e113f1d64"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 title-style capitalization}}.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Remove articles like\'a0a,\'a0an, and\'a0the\'a0from menu-item labels to save space.
\f1\b0 \'a0In English, articles always lengthen labels, but rarely enhance understanding. For example, changing a menu-item label from View Settings to View the Settings doesn\'92t provide additional clarification.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Show people when a menu item is unavailable.
\f1\b0 \'a0An unavailable menu item often appears dimmed and doesn\'92t respond to interactions. If all of a menu\'92s items are unavailable, the menu itself needs to remain available so people can open it and learn about the commands it contains.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Append an ellipsis to a menu item\'92s label when the action requires more information before it can complete.
\f1\b0 \'a0The ellipsis character (\'85) signals that people need to input information or make additional choices, typically within another view.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/menus#Icons"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Icons}}
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Represent menu item actions with familiar icons.
\f1\b0 \'a0Icons help people recognize common actions throughout your app. Use the same icons as the system to represent actions such as Copy, Share, and Delete, wherever they appear. For a list of icons that represent common actions, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/icons#Standard-icons"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Standard icons}}.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Don\'92t display an icon if you can\'92t find one that clearly represents the menu item.
\f1\b0 \'a0Not all menu items need an icon. Be careful when adding icons for custom menu items to avoid confusion with other existing actions, and don\'92t add icons just for the sake of ornamentation.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
