{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/menus#Organization"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Organization}}
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Organizing menu items in ways that reflect how people use your app or game can make your experience feel straightforward and easy to use.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Prefer listing important or frequently used menu items first.
\f1\b0 \'a0People tend to start scanning a menu from the top, so listing high-priority items first often means that people can find what they want without reading the entire menu.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Consider grouping logically related items.
\f1\b0 \'a0For example, grouping editing commands like Copy, Cut, and Paste or camera commands like Look Up, Look Down, and Look Left can help people remember where to find them. To help people visually distinguish such groups, use a separator. Depending on the platform and type of menu, a\'a0
\f4\i separator
\f1\i0 \'a0appears between groups of items as a horizontal line or a short gap in the menu\'92s background appearance.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Prefer keeping all logically related commands in the same group, even if the commands don\'92t all have the same importance.
\f1\b0 \'a0For example, people generally use Paste and Match Style much less often than they use Paste, but they expect to find both commands in the same group that contains more frequently used editing commands like Copy and Cut.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Be mindful of menu length.
\f1\b0 \'a0People need more time and attention to read a long menu, which means they may miss the command they want. If a menu is too long, consider dividing it into separate menus. Alternatively, you might be able to use a submenu to shorten the list, such as listing difficulty levels in a submenu of a New Game menu item. The exception is when a menu contains user-defined or dynamically generated content, like the History and Bookmarks menus in Safari. People expect such a menu to accommodate all the items they add to it, so a long menu is fine, and scrolling is acceptable.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/menus#Submenus"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Submenus}}
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Sometimes, a menu item can reveal a set of closely related items in a subordinate list called a\'a0
\f4\i submenu
\f1\i0 . A menu item indicates the presence of a submenu by displaying a symbol \'97 like a chevron \'97 after its label. Submenus are functionally identical to menus, aside from their hierarchical positioning.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Use submenus sparingly.
\f1\b0 \'a0Each submenu adds complexity to the interface and hides the items it contains. You might consider creating a submenu when a term appears in more than two menu items in the same group. For example, instead of offering separate menu items for Sort by Date, Sort by Score, and Sort by Time, a game could present a menu item that uses a submenu to list the sorting options Date, Score, and Time. It generally works well to use the repeated term \'97 in this case,\'a0
\f4\i Sort by
\f1\i0 \'a0\'97 in the menu item\'92s label to help people predict the contents of the submenu.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Limit the depth and length of submenus.
\f1\b0 \'a0It can be difficult for people to reveal multiple levels of hierarchical submenus, so it\'92s generally best to restrict them to a single level. Also, if a submenu contains more than about five items, consider creating a new menu.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Make sure a submenu remains available even when its nested menu items are unavailable.
\f1\b0 \'a0A submenu item \'97 like all menu items \'97 needs to let people open it and learn about the commands it contains.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Prefer using a submenu to indenting menu items.
\f1\b0 \'a0Using indentation is inconsistent with the system and doesn\'92t clearly express the relationships between the menu items.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/menus#Toggled-items"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Toggled items}}
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Menu items often represent attributes or objects that people can turn on or off. If you want to avoid listing a separate menu item for each state, it can be efficient to create a single, toggled menu item that communicates the current state and lets people change it.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Consider using a changeable label that describes an item\'92s current state.
\f1\b0 \'a0For example, instead of listing two menu items like Show Map and Hide Map, you could include one menu item whose label changes from Show Map to Hide Map, depending on whether the map is visible.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Include a verb if a changeable label isn\'92t clear enough.
\f1\b0 \'a0For example, people might not know whether the changeable labels HDR On and HDR Off describe actions or states. If you needed to clarify that these items represent actions, you could add verbs to the labels, like Turn HDR On and Turn HDR Off.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 If necessary, display both menu items instead of one toggled item.
\f1\b0 \'a0Sometimes, it helps people to view both actions or states at the same time. For example, a game could list both Take Account Online and Take Account Offline items, so when someone\'92s account is online, only the Take Account Offline menu item appears available.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Consider using a checkmark to show that an attribute is currently in effect.
\f1\b0 \'a0It\'92s easy for people to scan for checkmarks in a list of attributes to find the ones that are selected. For example, in the standard Format > Font menu, checkmarks can make it easy for people notice the styles that apply to selected text.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Consider offering a menu item that makes it easy to remove multiple toggled attributes.
\f1\b0 \'a0For example, if you let people apply several styles to selected text, it can work well to provide a menu item \'97 such as Plain \'97 that removes all applied formatting attributes at one time.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/menus#In-game-menus"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 In-game menus}}
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 In-game menus give players ways to control gameplay as well as determine\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/settings"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 settings}}\'a0for the game as a whole.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Let players navigate in-game menus using the platform\'92s default interaction method.
\f1\b0 \'a0People expect to use the same interactions to navigate your menus as they use for navigating other menus on the device. For example, players expect to navigate your game menus using touch in iOS and iPadOS, and direct and indirect gestures in visionOS.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Make sure your menus remain easy to open and read on all platforms you support.
\f1\b0 \'a0Each platform defines specific sizes that work best for fonts and interaction targets. Sometimes, scaling your game content to display on a different screen \'97 especially a mobile device screen \'97 can make in-game menus too small for people to read or interact with. If this happens, modify the size of the tap targets and consider alternative ways to communicate the menu\'92s content. For guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/typography"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Typography}}\'a0and\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/game-controls#Touch-controls"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Touch controls}}.\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa640\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs67\fsmilli33882 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Toolbars\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs39\fsmilli19765 \cf2 \cb3 A toolbar provides convenient access to frequently used commands, controls, navigation, and search.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \strokec2 {{\NeXTGraphic components-toolbar-intro~dark@2x.png \width29600 \height16640 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 A toolbar consists of one or more sets of controls arranged horizontally along the top or bottom edge of the view, grouped into logical sections.\cb1 \
\cb3 Toolbars act on content in the view, facilitate navigation, and help orient people in the app. They include three types of content:\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls17\ilvl0\cf2 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The title of the current view\cb1 \
\ls17\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Navigation controls, like back and forward, and\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/search-fields"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 search fields}}\cb1 \
\ls17\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Actions, or bar items, like\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/buttons"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 buttons}}\'a0and\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/menus"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 menus}}\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 In contrast to a toolbar, a\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/tab-bars"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 tab bar}}\'a0is specifically for navigating between areas of an app.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/toolbars#Best-practices"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Best practices}}
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Choose items deliberately to avoid overcrowding.
\f1\b0 \'a0People need to be able to distinguish and activate each item, so you don\'92t want to put too many items in the toolbar. To accommodate variable view widths, define which items move to the overflow menu as the toolbar becomes narrower.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf9 \cb10 \strokec9 Note\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \cb10 \strokec2 The system automatically adds an overflow menu in macOS or iPadOS when items no longer fit. Don\'92t add an overflow menu manually, and avoid layouts that cause toolbar items to overflow by default.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Add a More menu to contain additional actions.
\f1\b0 \'a0Prioritize less important actions for inclusion in the More menu. Try to include all actions in the toolbar if possible, and only add this menu if you really need it.\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
