\fs19\fsmilli9882 \cf2 \cb3 The standard toolbar in macOS Notes includes a More menu with extra commands.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa340\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 In iPadOS and macOS apps, consider letting people customize the toolbar to include their most common items.
\f1\b0 \'a0Toolbar customization is especially useful in apps that provide a lot of items \'97 or that include advanced functionality that not everyone needs \'97 and in apps that people tend to use for long periods of time. For example, it works well to make a range of editing actions available for toolbar customization, because people often use different types of editing commands based on their work style and their current project.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Reduce the use of toolbar backgrounds and tinted controls.
\f1\b0 \'a0Any custom backgrounds and appearances you use might overlay or interfere with background effects that the system provides. Instead, use the content layer to inform the color and appearance of the toolbar, and use a\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/SwiftUI/ScrollEdgeEffectStyle"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3 \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 ScrollEdgeEffectStyle}}\'a0when necessary to distinguish the toolbar area from the content area. This approach helps your app express its unique personality without distracting from content.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Avoid applying a similar color to toolbar item labels and content layer backgrounds.
\f1\b0 \'a0If your app already has bright, colorful content in the content layer, prefer using the default monochromatic appearance of toolbars. For more guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/color#Liquid-Glass-color"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Liquid Glass color}}.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Prefer using standard components in a toolbar.
\f1\b0 \'a0By default, standard buttons, text fields, headers, and footers have corner radii that are concentric with bar corners. If you need to create a custom component, ensure that its corner radius is also concentric with the bar\'92s corners.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Consider temporarily hiding toolbars for a distraction-free experience.
\f1\b0 \'a0Sometimes people appreciate a minimal interface to reduce distractions or reveal more content. If you support this, do so contextually when it makes the most sense, and offer ways to reliably restore hidden interface elements. For guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/going-full-screen"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Going full screen}}. For guidance specific to visionOS, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/immersive-experiences"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Immersive experiences}}.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/toolbars#Titles"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Titles}}
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Provide a useful title for each window.
\f1\b0 \'a0A title helps people confirm their location as they navigate your app, and differentiates between the content of multiple open windows. If titling a toolbar seems redundant, you can leave the title area empty. For example, Notes doesn\'92t title the current note when a single window is open, because the first line of content typically supplies sufficient context. However, when opening notes in separate windows, the system titles them with the first line of content so people can tell them apart.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Don\'92t title windows with your app name.
\f1\b0 \'a0Your app\'92s name doesn\'92t provide useful information about your content hierarchy or any window or area in your app, so it doesn\'92t work well as a title.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Write a concise title.
\f1\b0 \'a0Aim for a word or short phrase that distills the purpose of the window or view, and keep the title under 15 characters long so you leave enough room for other controls.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/toolbars#Navigation"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Navigation}}
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 A toolbar with navigation controls appears at the top of a window, helping people move through a hierarchy of content. A toolbar also often contains a\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/search-fields"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 search field}}\'a0for quick navigation between areas or pieces of content. In iOS, a navigation-specific toolbar is sometimes called a navigation bar.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Use the standard Back and Close buttons.
\f1\b0 \'a0People know that the standard Back button lets them retrace their steps through a hierarchy of information, and the standard Close button closes a modal view. Prefer the standard symbols for each, and don\'92t use a text label that says\'a0
\f4\i Back
\f1\i0 \'a0or\'a0
\f4\i Close
\f1\i0 . If you create a custom version of either, make sure it still looks the same, behaves as people expect, and matches the rest of your interface, and ensure you consistently implement it throughout your app or game. For guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/icons"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Icons}}.\cb1 \
