\f0\b\fs67\fsmilli33882 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Windows\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs39\fsmilli19765 \cf2 \cb3 A window presents UI views and components in your app or game.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \strokec2 {{\NeXTGraphic components-window-intro~dark@2x.png \width29600 \height16640 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 In iPadOS, macOS, and visionOS, windows help define the visual boundaries of app content and separate it from other areas of the system, and enable multitasking workflows both within and between apps. Windows include system-provided interface elements such as frames and window controls that let people open, close, resize, and relocate them.\cb1 \
\cb3 Conceptually, apps use two types of windows to display content:\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls20\ilvl0\cf2 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 A\'a0
\f4\i primary
\f1\i0 \'a0window presents the main navigation and content of an app, and actions associated with them.\cb1 \
\ls20\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 An\'a0
\f4\i auxiliary
\f1\i0 \'a0window presents a specific task or area in an app. Dedicated to one experience, an auxiliary window doesn\'92t allow navigation to other app areas, and it typically includes a button people use to close it after completing the task.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 For guidance laying out content within a window on any platform, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/layout"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Layout}}; for guidance laying out content in Apple\'a0Vision\'a0Pro space, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/spatial-layout"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Spatial layout}}. For developer guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/SwiftUI/Windows"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Windows}}.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/windows#Best-practices"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Best practices}}
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Make sure that your windows adapt fluidly to different sizes to support multitasking and multiwindow workflows.
\f1\b0 \'a0For guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/layout"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Layout}}\'a0and\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/multitasking"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Multitasking}}.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Choose the right moment to open a new window.
\f1\b0 \'a0Opening content in a separate window is great for helping people multitask or preserve context. For example, Mail opens a new window whenever someone selects the Compose action, so both the new message and the existing email are visible at the same time. However, opening new windows excessively creates clutter and can make navigating your app more confusing. Avoid opening new windows as default behavior unless it makes sense for your app.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Consider providing the option to view content in a new window.
\f1\b0 \'a0While it\'92s best to avoid opening new windows as default behavior unless it benefits your user experience, it\'92s also great to give people the flexibility of viewing content in multiple ways. Consider letting people view content in a new window using a command in a\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/context-menus"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 context menu}}\'a0or in the\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/the-menu-bar#File-menu"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 File menu}}. For developer guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/SwiftUI/OpenWindowAction"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3 \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 OpenWindowAction}}.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Avoid creating custom window UI.
\f1\b0 \'a0System-provided windows look and behave in a way that people understand and recognize. Avoid making custom window frames or controls, and don\'92t try to replicate the system-provided appearance. Doing so without perfectly matching the system\'92s look and behavior can make your app feel broken.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Use the term\'a0window\'a0in user-facing content.
\f1\b0 \'a0The system refers to app windows as\'a0
\f4\i windows
\f1\i0 \'a0regardless of type. Using different terms \'97 including\'a0
\f4\i scene
\f1\i0 , which refers to window implementation \'97 is likely to confuse people.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/windows#Platform-considerations"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Platform considerations}}
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f4\i\b0\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Not supported in iOS, tvOS, or watchOS.
\f1\i0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/windows#iPadOS"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs39\fsmilli19765 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 iPadOS}}
\fs39\fsmilli19765 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Windows present in one of two ways depending on a person\'92s choice in Multitasking & Gestures settings.\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls21\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Full screen.
\f1\b0 \'a0App windows fill the entire screen, and people switch between them \'97 or between multiple windows of the same app \'97 using the app switcher.\cb1 \
\ls21\ilvl0
\f2\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Windowed.
\f1\b0 \'a0People can freely resize app windows. Multiple windows can be onscreen at once, and people can reposition them and bring them to the front. The system remembers window size and placement even when an app is closed.\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls22\ilvl0
\fs19\fsmilli9882 \cf2 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/windows#"}}{\fldrslt \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Full screen}}\cb1 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 \uc0\u8232 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/windows#"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \cb3 \strokec5 Windowed}}
\fs34 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 {{\NeXTGraphic Attachment.png \width320 \height320 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa340\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Make sure window controls don\'92t overlap toolbar items.
\f1\b0 \'a0When windowed, app windows include window controls at the leading edge of the toolbar. If your app has toolbar buttons at the leading edge, they might be hidden by window controls when they appear. To prevent this, instead of placing buttons directly on the leading edge, move them inward when the window controls appear.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Consider letting people use a gesture to open content in a new window.
\f1\b0 \'a0For example, people can use the pinch gesture to expand a Notes item into a new window. For developer guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/UIKit/UICollectionViewDelegate/collectionView(_:sceneActivationConfigurationForItemAt:point:)"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3 \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 collectionView(_:sceneActivationConfigurationForItemAt:point:)}}\'a0(to transition from a collection view item), or\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/UIKit/UIWindowScene/ActivationInteraction"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3 \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 UIWindowScene.ActivationInteraction}}\'a0(to transition from an item in any other view).\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf17 \cb18 \strokec17 Tip\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \cb18 \strokec2 If you only need to let people view one file, you can present it without creating your own window, but you must support multiple windows in your app. For developer guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/QuickLook/QLPreviewSceneActivationConfiguration"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3 \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 QLPreviewSceneActivationConfiguration}}.\cf2 \cb1 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/windows#macOS"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs39\fsmilli19765 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 macOS}}
\fs39\fsmilli19765 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 In macOS, people typically run several apps at the same time, often viewing windows from multiple apps on one desktop and switching frequently between different windows \'97 moving, resizing, minimizing, and revealing the windows to suit their work style.\cb1 \
\cb3 To learn about setting up a window to display your game in macOS, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/Metal/managing-your-game-window-for-metal-in-macos"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Managing your game window for Metal in macOS}}.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/windows#macOS-window-anatomy"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs33\fsmilli16941 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 macOS window anatomy}}
\fs33\fsmilli16941 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 A macOS window consists of a frame and a body area. People can move a window by dragging the frame and can often resize the window by dragging its edges.\cb1 \
\cb3 The\'a0
\f4\i frame
\f1\i0 \'a0of a window appears above the body area and can include window controls and a\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/toolbars"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 toolbar}}. In rare cases, a window can also display a bottom bar, which is a part of the frame that appears below body content.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/windows#macOS-window-states"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs33\fsmilli16941 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 macOS window states}}
\fs33\fsmilli16941 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 A macOS window can have one of three states:\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls23\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Main.
\f1\b0 \'a0The frontmost window that people view is an app\'92s main window. There can be only one main window per app.\cb1 \
\ls23\ilvl0
\f2\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Key.
\f1\b0 \'a0Also called the\'a0
\f4\i active window
\f1\i0 , the key window accepts people\'92s input. There can be only one key window onscreen at a time. Although the front app\'92s main window is usually the key window, another window \'97 such as a panel floating above the main window \'97 might be key instead. People typically click a window to make it key; when people click an app\'92s Dock icon to bring all of that app\'92s windows forward, only the most recently accessed window becomes key.\cb1 \
\ls23\ilvl0
\f2\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Inactive.
\f1\b0 \'a0A window that\'92s not in the foreground is an inactive window.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 The system gives main, key, and inactive windows different appearances to help people visually identify them. For example, the key window uses color in the title bar options for closing, minimizing, and zooming; inactive windows and main windows that aren\'92t key use gray in these options. Also, inactive windows don\'92t use\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/materials"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 vibrancy}}\'a0(an effect that can pull color into a window from the content underneath it), which makes them appear subdued and seem visually farther away than the main and key windows.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 {{\NeXTGraphic Attachment.png \width320 \height320 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf9 \cb10 \strokec9 Note\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \cb10 \strokec2 Some windows \'97 typically, panels like Colors or Fonts \'97 become the key window only when people click the window\'92s title bar or a component that requires keyboard input, such as a text field.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Make sure custom windows use the system-defined appearances.
\f1\b0 \'a0People rely on the visual differences between windows to help them identify the foreground window and know which window will accept their input. When you use system-provided components, a window\'92s background and button appearances update automatically when the window changes state; if you use custom implementations, you need to do this work yourself.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Avoid putting critical information or actions in a bottom bar, because people often relocate a window in a way that hides its bottom edge.
\f1\b0 \'a0If you must include one, use it only to display a small amount of information directly related to a window\'92s contents or to a selected item within it. For example, Finder uses a bottom bar (called the status bar) to display the total number of items in a window, the number of selected items, and how much space is available on the disk. A bottom bar is small, so if you have more information to display, consider using an inspector, which typically presents information on the trailing side of a split view\cb1 \
\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa640\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs67\fsmilli33882 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Sheets\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs39\fsmilli19765 \cf2 \cb3 A sheet helps people perform a scoped task that\'92s closely related to their current context.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \strokec2 {{\NeXTGraphic components-sheet-intro~dark@2x.png \width29600 \height16640 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 By default, a sheet is\'a0
\f4\i modal
\f1\i0 , presenting a targeted experience that prevents people from interacting with the parent view until they dismiss the sheet (for more on modal presentation, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/modality"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Modality}}). A modal sheet is useful for requesting specific information from people or presenting a simple task that they can complete before returning to the parent view. For example, a sheet might let people supply information needed to complete an action, such as attaching a file, choosing the location for a move or save, or specifying the format for a selection.\cb1 \
\cb3 In macOS, visionOS, and watchOS, a sheet is always modal, but in iOS and iPadOS, a sheet can also be nonmodal. When a nonmodal sheet is onscreen, people use its functionality to directly affect the current task in the parent view without dismissing the sheet. For example, Notes on iPhone and iPad uses a nonmodal sheet to help people apply different formatting to various text selections as they edit a note.\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 {{\NeXTGraphic sheets-nonmodal-notes-text-regular~dark@2x.png \width10720 \height23240 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

\fs19\fsmilli9882 \cf2 \cb3 The Notes format sheet lets people apply formatting to selected text in the editing view.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa340\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 {{\NeXTGraphic sheets-nonmodal-notes-text-italic~dark@2x.png \width10720 \height23240 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

\fs19\fsmilli9882 \cf2 \cb3 Because the sheet is nonmodal, people can make additional text selections without dismissing the sheet.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa340\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/sheets#Best-practices"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Best practices}}
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Use a sheet to present simple content or tasks.
\f1\b0 \'a0A sheet allows some of the parent view to remain visible, helping people retain their original context as they interact with the sheet.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 For complex or prolonged user flows, consider alternatives to sheets.
\f1\b0 \'a0For example, iOS and iPadOS offer a full-screen style of modal view that can work well to display content like videos, photos, or camera views or to help people perform multistep tasks like document or photo editing. (For developer guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/UIKit/UIModalPresentationStyle/fullScreen"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3 \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 UIModalPresentationStyle.fullScreen}}.) In a macOS experience, you might want to open a new window or let people enter full-screen mode instead of using a sheet. For example, a self-contained task like editing a document tends to work well in a separate window, whereas\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/going-full-screen"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 going full screen}}\'a0can help people view media. In visionOS, you can give people a way to transition your app to a Full Space where they can dive into content or a task; for guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/immersive-experiences"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Immersive experiences}}.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Display only one sheet at a time from the main interface.
\f1\b0 \'a0When people close a sheet, they expect to return to the parent view or window. If closing a sheet takes people back to another sheet, they can lose track of where they are in your app. If something people do within a sheet results in another sheet appearing, close the first sheet before displaying the new one. If necessary, you can display the first sheet again after people dismiss the second one.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Use a nonmodal view when you want to present supplementary items that affect the main task in the parent view.
\f1\b0 \'a0To give people access to information and actions they need while continuing to interact with the main window, consider using a\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/split-views"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 split view}}\'a0in visionOS or a\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/panels"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 panel}}\'a0in macOS; in iOS and iPadOS, you can use a nonmodal sheet for this workflow. For guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/sheets#iOS-iPadOS"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 iOS, iPadOS}}.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/sheets#Platform-considerations"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Platform considerations}}
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f4\i\b0\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 No additional considerations for tvOS.
\f1\i0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/sheets#iOS-iPadOS"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs39\fsmilli19765 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 iOS, iPadOS}}
\fs39\fsmilli19765 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 A resizable sheet expands when people scroll its contents or drag the\'a0
\f4\i grabber
\f1\i0 , which is a small horizontal indicator that can appear at the top edge of a sheet. Sheets resize according to their\'a0
\f4\i detents
\f1\i0 , which are particular heights at which a sheet naturally rests. Designed for iPhone, detents specify particular heights at which a sheet naturally rests. The system defines two detents:\'a0
\f4\i large
\f1\i0 \'a0is the height of a fully expanded sheet and\'a0
\f4\i medium
\f1\i0 \'a0is about half of the fully expanded height.\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 {{\NeXTGraphic Attachment.png \width320 \height320 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

\fs19\fsmilli9882 \cf2 \cb3 Large detent\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa340\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 {{\NeXTGraphic Attachment.png \width320 \height320 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

\fs19\fsmilli9882 \cf2 \cb3 Medium detent\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa340\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 Sheets automatically support the large detent. Adding the medium detent allows the sheet to rest at both heights, whereas specifying only medium prevents the sheet from expanding to full height. For developer guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/UIKit/UISheetPresentationController/detents"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3 \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 detents}}.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 In an iPhone app, consider supporting the medium detent to allow progressive disclosure of the sheet\'92s content.
\f1\b0 \'a0For example, a share sheet displays the most relevant items within the medium detent, where they\'92re visible without resizing. To view more items, people can scroll or expand the sheet. In contrast, you might not want to support the medium detent if a sheet\'92s content is more useful when it displays at full height. For example, the compose sheets in Messages and Mail display only at full height to give people enough room to create content.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Include a grabber in a resizable sheet.
\f1\b0 \'a0A grabber shows people that they can drag the sheet to resize it; they can also tap it to cycle through the detents. In addition to providing a visual indicator of resizability, a grabber also works with VoiceOver so people can resize the sheet without seeing the screen. For developer guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/UIKit/UISheetPresentationController/prefersGrabberVisible"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3 \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 prefersGrabberVisible}}.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Support swiping to dismiss a sheet.
\f1\b0 \'a0People expect to swipe vertically to dismiss a sheet instead of tapping a dismiss button. If people have unsaved changes in the sheet when they begin swiping to dismiss it, use an action sheet to let them confirm their action.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Position Done and Cancel buttons as people expect.
\f1\b0 \'a0Typically, a Done or Dismiss button belongs in a sheet\'92s top-right corner in a left-to-right layout. The Cancel button belongs in a sheet\'92s top-left corner.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 The exception to this is for sheets with additional subviews, where the Cancel button belongs in the top-right; this provides room for the Back button in the top-left on pages after the first. At the end of the navigation flow, replace the Cancel button with the Done button.\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 {{\NeXTGraphic Attachment.png \width320 \height320 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

\fs19\fsmilli9882 \cf2 \cb3 Placement of the Cancel button when it appears by itself\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa340\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 {{\NeXTGraphic Attachment.png \width320 \height320 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

\fs19\fsmilli9882 \cf2 \cb3 Placement of the Cancel button when it appears as part of a multi-step flow\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa340\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Prefer using the page or form sheet presentation styles in an iPadOS app.
\f1\b0 \'a0Each style uses a default size for the sheet, centering its content on top of a dimmed background view and providing a consistent experience. For developer guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/UIKit/UIModalPresentationStyle"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3 \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 UIModalPresentationStyle}}.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/sheets#macOS"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs39\fsmilli19765 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 macOS}}
\fs39\fsmilli19765 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 In macOS, a sheet is a cardlike view with rounded corners that floats on top of its parent window. The parent window is dimmed while the sheet is onscreen, signaling that people can\'92t interact with it until they dismiss the sheet. However, people expect to interact with other app windows before dismissing a sheet.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 {{\NeXTGraphic Attachment.png \width320 \height320 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Present a sheet in a reasonable default size.
\f1\b0 \'a0People don\'92t generally expect to resize sheets, so it\'92s important to use a size that\'92s appropriate for the content you display. In some cases, however, people appreciate a resizable sheet \'97 such as when they need to expand the contents for a clearer view \'97 so it\'92s a good idea to support resizing.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Let people interact with other app windows without first dismissing a sheet.
\f1\b0 \'a0When a sheet opens, you bring its parent window to the front \'97 if the parent window is a document window, you also bring forward its modeless document-related panels. When people want to interact with other windows in your app, make sure they can bring those windows forward even if they haven\'92t dismissed the sheet yet.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Position a sheet\'92s dismiss buttons as people expect.
\f1\b0 \'a0People expect to find all buttons that dismiss a sheet \'97 including Done, OK, and Cancel \'97 at the bottom of the view, in the trailing corner.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Use a panel instead of a sheet if people need to repeatedly provide input and observe results.
\f1\b0 \'a0A find and replace panel, for example, might let people initiate replacements individually, so they can observe the result of each search for correctness. For guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/panels"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Panels}}.\cb1 \
\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa640\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs67\fsmilli33882 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Pickers\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs39\fsmilli19765 \cf2 \cb3 A picker displays one or more scrollable lists of distinct values that people can choose from.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \strokec2 {{\NeXTGraphic Attachment.png \width320 \height320 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 The system provides several styles of pickers, each of which offers different types of selectable values and has a different appearance. The exact values shown in a picker, and their order, depend on the device language.\cb1 \
\cb3 Pickers help people enter information by letting them choose single or multipart values. Date pickers specifically offer additional ways to choose values, like selecting a day in a calendar view or entering dates and times using a numeric keypad.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/pickers#Best-practices"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Best practices}}
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Consider using a picker to offer medium-to-long lists of items.
\f1\b0 \'a0If you need to display a fairly short list of choices, consider using a\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/pull-down-buttons"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 pull-down button}}\'a0instead of a picker. Although a picker makes it easy to scroll quickly through many items, it may add too much visual weight to a short list of items. On the other hand, if you need to present a very large set of items, consider using a\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/lists-and-tables"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 list or table}}. Lists and tables can adjust in height, and tables can include an index, which makes it much faster to target a section of the list.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Use predictable and logically ordered values.
\f1\b0 \'a0Before people interact with a picker, many of its values can be hidden. It\'92s best when people can predict what the hidden values are, such as with an alphabetized list of countries, so they can move through the items quickly.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Avoid switching views to show a picker.
\f1\b0 \'a0A picker works well when displayed in context, below or in proximity to the field people are editing. A picker typically appears at the bottom of a window or in a popover.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Consider providing less granularity when specifying minutes in a date picker.
\f1\b0 \'a0By default, a minute list includes 60 values (0 to 59). You can optionally increase the minute interval as long as it divides evenly into 60. For example, you might want quarter-hour intervals (0, 15, 30, and 45).\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/pickers#Platform-considerations"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Platform considerations}}
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f4\i\b0\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 No additional considerations for visionOS.
\f1\i0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/pickers#iOS-iPadOS"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs39\fsmilli19765 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 iOS, iPadOS}}
\fs39\fsmilli19765 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 A date picker is an efficient interface for selecting a specific date, time, or both, using touch, a keyboard, or a pointing device. You can display a date picker in one of the following styles:\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls24\ilvl0\cf2 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Compact \'97 A button that displays editable date and time content in a modal view.\cb1 \
\ls24\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Inline \'97 For time only, a button that displays wheels of values; for dates and times, an inline calendar view.\cb1 \
\ls24\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Wheels \'97 A set of scrolling wheels that also supports data entry through built-in or external keyboards.\cb1 \
\ls24\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Automatic \'97 A system-determined style based on the current platform and date picker mode.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 A date picker has four modes, each of which presents a different set of selectable values.\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls25\ilvl0\cf2 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Date \'97 Displays months, days of the month, and years.\cb1 \
\ls25\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Time \'97 Displays hours, minutes, and (optionally) an AM/PM designation.\cb1 \
\ls25\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Date and time \'97 Displays dates, hours, minutes, and (optionally) an AM/PM designation.\cb1 \
\ls25\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Countdown timer \'97 Displays hours and minutes, up to a maximum of 23 hours and 59 minutes. This mode isn\'92t available in the inline or compact styles.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 The exact values shown in a date picker, and their order, depend on the device location.\cb1 \
\cb3 Here are several examples of date pickers showing different combinations of style and mode.\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls26\ilvl0
\fs19\fsmilli9882 \cf2 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/pickers#"}}{\fldrslt \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Compact}}\cb1 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 \uc0\u8232 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/pickers#"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \cb3 \strokec5 Inline}}\cf5 \strokec5 \uc0\u8232 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/pickers#"}}{\fldrslt \cb3 Wheels}}
