\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

\fs19\fsmilli9882 \cf2 \cb3 In a compact layout, a picker opens as a popover over your content.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa340\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Use a compact date picker when space is constrained.
\f1\b0 \'a0The compact style displays a button that shows the current value in your app\'92s accent color. When people tap the button, the date picker opens a modal view, providing access to a familiar calendar-style editor and time picker. Within the modal view, people can make multiple edits to dates and times before tapping outside the view to confirm their choices.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/pickers#macOS"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs39\fsmilli19765 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 macOS}}
\fs39\fsmilli19765 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Choose a date picker style that suits your app.
\f1\b0 \'a0There are two styles of date pickers in macOS: textual and graphical. The textual style is useful when you\'92re working with limited space and you expect people to make specific date and time selections. The graphical style is useful when you want to give people the option of browsing through days in a calendar or selecting a range of dates, or when the look of a clock face is appropriate for your app.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 For developer guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/AppKit/NSDatePicker"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3 \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 NSDatePicker}}.\cb1 \
\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa640\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs67\fsmilli33882 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Segmented controls\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs39\fsmilli19765 \cf2 \cb3 A segmented control is a linear set of two or more segments, each of which functions as a button.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \strokec2 {{\NeXTGraphic components-segmented-control-intro~dark@2x.png \width29600 \height16640 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 Within a segmented control, all segments are usually equal in width. Like\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/buttons"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 buttons}}, segments can contain text or images. Segments can also have text labels beneath them (or beneath the control as a whole).\cb1 \
\cb3 A segmented control offers a single choice from among a set of options, or in macOS, either a single choice or multiple choices. For example, in macOS Keynote people can select only one segment in the alignment options control to align selected text. In contrast, people can choose multiple segments in the font attributes control to combine styles like bold, italics, and underline. The toolbar of a Keynote window also uses a segmented control to let people show and hide various editing panes within the main window area.\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 {{\NeXTGraphic segmented-control-one-choice~dark@2x.png \width12000 \height1760 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

\fs19\fsmilli9882 \cf2 \cb3 Single choice\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa340\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 {{\NeXTGraphic segmented-control-multiple-choices~dark@2x.png \width12000 \height1760 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

\fs19\fsmilli9882 \cf2 \cb3 Multiple choices\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa340\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 In addition to representing the state of a single or multiple-choice selection, a segmented control can function as a set of buttons that perform actions without showing a selection state. For example, the Reply, Reply all, and Forward buttons in macOS Mail. For developer guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/UIKit/UISegmentedControl/isMomentary"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3 \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 isMomentary}}\'a0and\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/AppKit/NSSegmentedControl/SwitchTracking/momentary"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3 \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 NSSegmentedControl.SwitchTracking.momentary}}.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/segmented-controls#Best-practices"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Best practices}}
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Use a segmented control to provide closely related choices that affect an object, state, or view.
\f1\b0 \'a0For example, a segmented control in an inspector could let people choose one or more attributes to apply to a selection, or a segmented control in a toolbar could offer a set of actions to perform on the current view.\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 {{\NeXTGraphic segmented-controls-activity-charts~dark@2x.png \width10720 \height11600 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

\fs19\fsmilli9882 \cf2 \cb3 In the iOS Health app, a segmented control provides a choice of time ranges for the activity graphs to display.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa340\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Consider a segmented control when it\'92s important to group functions together, or to clearly show their selection state.
\f1\b0 \'a0Unlike other button styles, segmented controls preserve their grouping regardless of the view size or where they appear. This grouping can also help people understand at a glance which controls are currently selected.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Keep control types consistent within a single segmented control.
\f1\b0 \'a0Don\'92t assign actions to segments in a control that otherwise represents selection state, and don\'92t show a selection state for segments in a control that otherwise performs actions.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Limit the number of segments in a control.
\f1\b0 \'a0Too many segments can be hard to parse and time-consuming to navigate. Aim for no more than about five to seven segments in a wide interface and no more than about five segments on iPhone.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 In general, keep segment size consistent.
\f1\b0 \'a0When all segments have equal width, a segmented control feels balanced. To the extent possible, it\'92s best to keep icon and title widths consistent too.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/segmented-controls#Content"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Content}}
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Prefer using either text or images \'97 not a mix of both \'97 in a single segmented control.
\f1\b0 \'a0Although individual segments can contain text labels or images, mixing the two in a single control can lead to a disconnected and confusing interface.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 As much as possible, use content with a similar size in each segment.
\f1\b0 \'a0Because all segments typically have equal width, it doesn\'92t look good if content fills some segments but not others.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Use nouns or noun phrases for segment labels.
\f1\b0 \'a0Write text that describes each segment and uses\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://support.apple.com/guide/applestyleguide/c-apsgb744e4a3/web#apdca93e113f1d64"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 title-style capitalization}}. A segmented control that displays text labels doesn\'92t need introductory text.\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa640\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs67\fsmilli33882 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Toggles\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs39\fsmilli19765 \cf2 \cb3 A toggle lets people choose between a pair of opposing states, like on and off, using a different appearance to indicate each state.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \strokec2 {{\NeXTGraphic components-toggles-intro~dark@2x.png \width29600 \height16640 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 A toggle can have various styles, such as switch and checkbox, and different platforms can use these styles in different ways. For guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/toggles#Platform-considerations"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 Platform considerations}}.\cb1 \
\cb3 In addition to toggles, all platforms also support buttons that behave like toggles by using a different appearance for each state. For developer guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/SwiftUI/ToggleStyle"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3 \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 ToggleStyle}}.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/toggles#Best-practices"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Best practices}}
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Use a toggle to help people choose between two opposing values that affect the state of content or a view.
\f1\b0 \'a0A toggle always lets people manage the state of something, so if you need to support other types of actions \'97 such as choosing from a list of items \'97 use a different component, like a\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/pop-up-buttons"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 pop-up button}}.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Clearly identify the setting, view, or content the toggle affects.
\f1\b0 \'a0In general, the surrounding context provides enough information for people to understand what they\'92re turning on or off. In some cases, often in macOS apps, you can also supply a label to describe the state the toggle controls. If you use a button that behaves like a toggle, you generally use an interface icon that communicates its purpose, and you update its appearance \'97 typically by changing the background \'97 based on the current state.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Make sure the visual differences in a toggle\'92s state are obvious.
\f1\b0 \'a0For example, you might add or remove a color fill, show or hide the background shape, or change the inner details you display \'97 like a checkmark or dot \'97 to show that a toggle is on or off. Avoid relying solely on different colors to communicate state, because not everyone can perceive the differences.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/toggles#Platform-considerations"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Platform considerations}}
\f0\b\fs45\fsmilli22588 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f4\i\b0\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 No additional considerations for tvOS, visionOS, or watchOS.
\f1\i0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/toggles#iOS-iPadOS"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs39\fsmilli19765 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 iOS, iPadOS}}
\fs39\fsmilli19765 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Use the switch toggle style only in a list row.
\f1\b0 \'a0You don\'92t need to supply a label in this situation because the content in the row provides the context for the state the switch controls.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Change the default color of a switch only if necessary.
\f1\b0 \'a0The default green color tends to work well in most cases, but you might want to use your app\'92s accent color instead. Be sure to use a color that provides enough contrast with the uncolored appearance to be perceptible.\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 {{\NeXTGraphic toggles-ios-default-color~dark@2x.png \width13400 \height6520 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

\fs19\fsmilli9882 \cf2 \cb3 Standard switch color\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa340\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 {{\NeXTGraphic toggles-ios-custom-color~dark@2x.png \width13400 \height6520 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

\fs19\fsmilli9882 \cf2 \cb3 Custom switch color\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa340\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Outside of a list, use a button that behaves like a toggle, not a switch.
\f1\b0 \'a0For example, the Phone app uses a toggle on the filter button to let users filter their recent calls. The app adds a blue highlight to indicate when the toggle is active, and removes it when the toggle is inactive.\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 {{\NeXTGraphic toggles-ios-phone-filter-on~dark@2x.png \width10720 \height11600 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

\fs19\fsmilli9882 \cf2 \cb3 The Phone app uses a toggle to switch between all recent calls and various filter options. When someone chooses a filter, the toggle appears with a custom background drawn behind the symbol.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa340\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 {{\NeXTGraphic toggles-ios-phone-filter-off~dark@2x.png \width10720 \height11600 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

\fs19\fsmilli9882 \cf2 \cb3 When someone returns to the main Recents view, the toggle appears without anything behind the symbol.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa340\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Avoid supplying a label that explains the button\'92s purpose.
\f1\b0 \'a0The interface icon you create \'97 combined with the alternative background appearances you supply \'97 help people understand what the button does. For developer guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/UIKit/UIButton/changesSelectionAsPrimaryAction"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3 \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 changesSelectionAsPrimaryAction}}.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/toggles#macOS"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs39\fsmilli19765 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 macOS}}
\fs39\fsmilli19765 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 In addition to the switch toggle style, macOS supports the checkbox style and also defines radio buttons that can provide similar behaviors.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Use switches, checkboxes, and radio buttons in the window body, not the window frame.
\f1\b0 \'a0In particular, avoid using these components in a toolbar or status bar.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/toggles#Switches"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs33\fsmilli16941 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Switches}}
\fs33\fsmilli16941 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Prefer a switch for settings that you want to emphasize.
\f1\b0 \'a0A switch has more visual weight than a checkbox, so it looks better when it controls more functionality than a checkbox typically does. For example, you might use a switch to let people turn on or off a group of settings, instead of just one setting. For developer guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/SwiftUI/ToggleStyle/switch"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3 \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 switch}}.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Within a grouped form, consider using a mini switch to control the setting in a single row.
\f1\b0 \'a0The height of a mini switch is similar to the height of buttons and other controls, resulting in rows that have a consistent height. If you need to present a hierarchy of settings within a grouped form, you can use a regular switch for the primary setting and mini switches for the subordinate settings. For developer guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/SwiftUI/GroupedFormStyle"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3 \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 GroupedFormStyle}}\'a0and\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/SwiftUI/ControlSize"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3 \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 ControlSize}}.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 In general, don\'92t replace a checkbox with a switch.
\f1\b0 \'a0If you\'92re already using a checkbox in your interface, it\'92s probably best to keep using it.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/toggles#Checkboxes"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs33\fsmilli16941 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Checkboxes}}
\fs33\fsmilli16941 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 A checkbox is a small, square button that\'92s empty when the button is off, contains a checkmark when the button is on, and can contain a dash when the button\'92s state is mixed. Typically, a checkbox includes a title on its trailing side. In an editable checklist, a checkbox can appear without a title or any additional content.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Use a checkbox instead of a switch if you need to present a hierarchy of settings.
\f1\b0 \'a0The visual style of checkboxes helps them align well and communicate grouping. By using alignment \'97 generally along the leading edge of the checkboxes \'97 and indentation, you can show dependencies, such as when the state of a checkbox governs the state of subordinate checkboxes.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 {{\NeXTGraphic Attachment.png \width320 \height320 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Consider using radio buttons if you need to present a set of more than two mutually exclusive options.
\f1\b0 \'a0When people need to choose from options in addition to just \'93on\'94 or \'93off,\'94 using multiple radio buttons can help you clarify each option with a unique label.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Consider using a label to introduce a group of checkboxes if their relationship isn\'92t clear.
\f1\b0 \'a0Describe the set of options, and align the label\'92s baseline with the first checkbox in the group.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Accurately reflect a checkbox\'92s state in its appearance.
\f1\b0 \'a0A checkbox\'92s state can be on, off, or mixed. If you use a checkbox to globally turn on and off multiple subordinate checkboxes, show a mixed state when the subordinate checkboxes have different states. For example, you might need to present a text-style setting that turns all styles on or off, but also lets people choose a subset of individual style settings like bold, italic, or underline. For developer guidance, see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/documentation/AppKit/NSButton/allowsMixedState"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3 \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 allowsMixedState}}.\cb1 \
\
