\fs34 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Prefer a set of radio buttons to present mutually exclusive options.
\f1\b0 \'a0If you need to let people choose multiple options in a set, use checkboxes instead.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Avoid listing too many radio buttons in a set.
\f1\b0 \'a0A long list of radio buttons takes up a lot of space in the interface and can be overwhelming. If you need to present more than about five options, consider using a component like a\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/pop-up-buttons"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 pop-up button}}\'a0instead.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 To present a single setting that can be on or off, prefer a checkbox.
\f1\b0 \'a0Although a single radio button can also turn something on or off, the presence or absence of the checkmark in a checkbox can make the current state easier to understand at a glance. In rare cases where a single checkbox doesn\'92t clearly communicate the opposing states, you can use a pair of radio buttons, each with a label that specifies the state it controls.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Use consistent spacing when you display radio buttons horizontally.
\f1\b0 \'a0Measure the space needed to accommodate the longest button label, and use that measurement consistently.\cb1 \
